SIMPLE: world
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: World
<hw>World</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>world</ets>,
<ets>werld</ets>, <ets>weorld</ets>, <ets>weoreld</ets>, AS.
<ets>weorold</ets>, <ets>worold</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>werold</ets>, D.
<ets>wereld</ets>, OHG. <ets>weralt</ets>, <ets>worolt</ets>,
<ets>werolt</ets>, <ets>werlt</ets>, G. <ets>welt</ets>, Icel.
<ets>ver⟦oum⟧ld</ets>, Sw. <ets>verld</ets>, Dan. <ets>verden</ets>;
properly, the age of man, lifetime, humanity; AS. <ets>wer</ets> a man +
a word akin to E. <ets>old</ets>; cf. AS. <ets>yld</ets> lifetime, age,
<ets>ylde</ets> men, humanity. Cf. <er>Werewolf</er>,
<er>Old</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The earth and the surrounding heavens; the creation;
the system of created things; existent creation; the universe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The invisible things of him from the creation of the
<qex>world</qex> are clearly seen.</q> <rj><qau>Rom. 1.
20.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With desire to know,⟦br⟧
What nearer might concern him, how this <qex>world</qex>⟦br⟧
Of heaven and earth conspicuous first began.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any planet or heavenly body, especially when
considered as inhabited, and as the scene of interests analogous with
human interests; <as>as, a plurality of <ex>worlds</ex></as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Lord of the <xex>worlds</xex> above.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>I.
Watts.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Amongst innumerable stars, that shone⟦br⟧
Star distant, but high-hand seemed other <qex>worlds</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There may be other <qex>worlds</qex>, where the inhabitants have
never violated their allegiance to their almighty Sovereign.</q>
<rj><qau>W. B. Sprague.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The earth and its inhabitants, with their concerns;
the sum of human affairs and interests.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That forbidden tree, whose mortal taste⟦br⟧
Brought death into the <qex>world</qex>, and all our woe.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>In a more restricted sense, that part of the earth
and its concerns which is known to any one, or contemplated by any one;
a division of the globe, or of its inhabitants; human affairs as seen
from a certain position, or from a given point of view; also, state of
existence; scene of life and action; <as>as, the Old <ex>World</ex>; the
New <ex>World</ex>; the religious <ex>world</ex>; the Catholic
<ex>world</ex>; the upper <ex>world</ex>; the future <ex>world</ex>; the
heathen <ex>world</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One of the greatest in the Christian <qex>world</qex>⟦br⟧
Shall be my surety.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Murmuring that now they must be put to make war beyond the
<qex>world's</qex> end -- for so they counted Britain.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The customs, practices, and interests of men;
general affairs of life; human society; public affairs and occupations;
<as>as, a knowledge of the <ex>world</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Happy is she that from the <qex>world</qex> retires.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If knowledge of the <qex>world</qex> makes man perfidious,⟦br⟧
May Juba ever live in ignorance.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Individual experience of, or concern with, life;
course of life; sum of the affairs which affect the individual; <as>as,
to begin the <ex>world</ex> with no property; to lose all, and begin the
<ex>world</ex> anew</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The inhabitants of the earth; the human race; people
in general; the public; mankind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Since I do purpose to marry, I will think nothing to any purpose
that the <qex>world</qex> can say against it.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tell me, wench, how will the <qex>world</qex> repute me⟦br⟧
For undertaking so unstaid a journey?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>The earth and its affairs as distinguished from
heaven; concerns of this life as distinguished from those of the life to
come; the present existence and its interests; hence, secular affairs;
engrossment or absorption in the affairs of this life; worldly
corruption; the ungodly or wicked part of mankind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I pray not for the <qex>world</qex>, but for them which thou hast
given me; for they are thine.</q> <rj><qau>John xvii. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Love not the <qex>world</qex>, neither the things that are in the
<qex>world</qex>. If any man love the <qex>world</qex>, the love of the
Father is not in him. For all that is in the <qex>world</qex>, the lust
of the flesh, and the lust of the eyes, and the pride of life, is not of
the Father, but is of the <qex>world</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>1 John ii. 15,
16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>As an emblem of immensity, a great multitude or
quantity; a large number.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>world</xex> of men.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Chapman.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>world</xex> of blossoms for the
bee.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Bryant.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor doth this wood lack <qex>worlds</qex> of company.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>world</qex> of woes dispatched in little space.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>All . . . in the world</b></col>, <cd>all that exists;
all that is possible; <as>as, <ex>all</ex> the precaution <ex>in the
world</ex> would not save him</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>A world to
see</b></col>, <cd>a wonder to see; something admirable or surprising to
see.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, you are novices; 't is a <qex>world to see</qex>⟦br⟧
How tame, when men and women are alone,⟦br⟧
A meacock wretch can make the curstest shrew.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <col><b>For all the world</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>Precisely;
exactly.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>For any consideration.</cd> --
<col><b>Seven wonders of the world</b></col>. <cd>See in the Dictionary
of Noted Names in Fiction.</cd> -- <col><b>To go to the world</b></col>,
<cd>to be married.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Thus <xex>goes</xex>
every one <xex>to the world</xex> but I . . . ; I may sit in a corner
and cry heighho for a husband!⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>World's
end</b></col>, <cd>the end, or most distant part, of the world; the
remotest regions.</cd> -- <col><b>World without end</b></col>,
<cd>eternally; forever; everlastingly; as if in a state of existence
having no end.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Throughout all ages, <qex>world without end</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Eph. iii. 21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Worldliness</ent>⟦br⟧
